--- body ---
## Context

RDJ-26561 R&R (tracker 0274), remark R1-06. Instead of only defending the
grey-literature boundary (ticket 0281), the author decided to extend it
within the existing international-institution frame: a curated layer of
key documents in two sub-lists.

**UNFCCC sub-list.** COP/CMP/CMA decisions bearing on finance (Copenhagen
$100bn, Paris Article 9 package, NCQG), Standing Committee on Finance
reports — especially the Biennial Assessments, which define climate finance
accounting — GCF/GEF/Adaptation Fund reports to COP, and pre-1995 INC
negotiation documents. Order of magnitude 150–300 documents.

**OECD DAC sub-list** (added 2026-07-20 after a corpus probe). The refined
corpus already holds 310 OECD-DOI (10.1787) works via OpenAlex, including
the flagship accounting series (USD 100 Billion Goal 2015; Provided and
Mobilised aggregate trends; DAC blended-finance guidance) and the Oxfam
Shadow Report counter-literature — so NO wholesale OECD harvest. The gaps
are the founding documents outside the DOI system: the DAC Statistical
Reporting Directives establishing the Rio markers (1998 onwards — zero
source directives in corpus, one academic paper about them), Development
Co-operation Reports (zero hits), and early DAC/WP-STAT/ENVIRONET documents
(corpus OECD-DOI coverage starts at 2000). Order of magnitude a few dozen
documents, from the OECD OLIS/One archive.

Known data properties (assessed 2026-07-20, verify at harvest):
- **No native abstracts** — derive abstract-equivalents (executive summaries,
  decision preambles) via the existing abstract-reconstruction pathway,
  flagged as reconstructed.
- **Fulltext**: open PDFs from the UNFCCC document portal (six official
  languages) and OECD OLIS/One; no clean public API on either (expect
  scraping or manual bulk export). Early material (INC, first COPs, 1990s
  DAC directives) is often scanned — OCR needed precisely for the pre-2007
  period the history cares about.
- **No DOIs, no reference lists** — the layer joins the text/embedding layer
  but stays outside citations.csv; disclose in the paper's bias section.
  (Recent OECD publications DO carry 10.1787 DOIs and are already in via
  OpenAlex — the dedup test below guards against re-adding them.)
- **No redistribution restriction** — derived text can ship in the deposit,
  unlike publisher-restricted academic abstracts.
- Document symbols (e.g. FCCC/CP/2009/11/Add.1, DCD/DAC(2016)3/FINAL) are
  the natural identifiers.

## Empirical basis (added 2026-07-22, author's angle)

The extension is bounded empirically, not by an a priori institution list:
cross the resubmitted Œconomia manuscript's bibliography against the v1
corpus and let the classes of absent-but-needed documents define the harvest.
Probe result (81 works cited, 31 in corpus; script and full class analysis in
`deliverables/data-paper/revision-rdj26561/biblio-vs-corpus-probe.md`):

- The only absent classes the manuscript actually needed are the official
  international-institution documents already targeted — UNFCCC decisions and
  the Biennial Assessment series (the corpus holds the 5th BA but not the
  2014 first edition, and commentary about Bali/Copenhagen/Cancún rather
  than the decisions themselves), plus GEF-type reports. The sub-lists above
  are confirmed; no open-ended new class emerges.
- Boundary decisions SETTLED by the author (2026-07-22): party/negotiating-
  bloc submissions (e.g. AOSIS on the NCQG) and negotiation-record commentary
  (IISD Earth Negotiations Bulletin summaries, statements at COPs) are
  INCLUDED — both sub-lists extend accordingly. Carbon markets and ESG stay
  DELIBERATE corpus-scope exclusions, to be stated in the paper's scope/bias
  section: MacKenzie 2009 (CDM/HFC-23 commensuration) and Golka 2024
  (ESG/impact-investing epistemics, zero climate-finance occurrence in
  abstract/keywords/intro) were verified on the documents — their absence is
  by design, not a query gap.
- Regression check: rerun the probe against corpus v2 after the harvest —
  classes A and B in the probe note should then match.

Sequencing warning: this is the largest work item of the revision and blocks
the final corpus numbers (every {{< meta >}} count refreshes). Start early;
prose tickets can draft against v1 numbers but the final render waits for
this. The `in_v1` flag preserves v1 reproducibility for the Œconomia
companion; the new corpus ships in 0280's new Zenodo version.

## Relevant files

- `scripts/catalog_*` — existing source harvesters, pattern for a new one
- Grey-literature seed mechanism (16 curated reports + World Bank API) —
  the layer extends this source, `from_grey` provenance flag
- `scripts/enrich_*` — abstract-reconstruction pathway to extend
- `config/` keyword taxonomy — finance-relevance rule for COP decisions
- Ticket 0280 — the deposit version this layer ships in

## Actions

1. Freeze the inclusion rule (proposal, amended per the 2026-07-22 decisions:
   official documents produced by or addressed to the COP or the OECD DAC
   that define, account for, or govern climate finance — including party/bloc
   submissions — plus the negotiation record around those decisions: session
   summaries such as the IISD Earth Negotiations Bulletin and statements
   delivered at COPs) and the two key-document sub-lists; author validates
   both BEFORE harvesting. Carbon markets and ESG remain outside corpus
   scope by design.
2. Build the harvester/curated importer: metadata (UN symbol, title, year,
   language, body), PDF retrieval, text extraction with OCR fallback.
3. Derive abstract-equivalents, flagged as reconstructed; embed via the
   standard multilingual pipeline.
4. Integrate as a Phase-1 source (provenance flag, dedup against existing
   grey seeds — some of the 16 are likely UNFCCC documents), rerun Phase 1
   on padme (coordinate with author; data flows padme→doudou).
5. Refresh corpus numbers and the paper's source/bias sections; update
   @tbl-sources and @tbl-quality.

## Test

- Harvester unit-tested on fixture metadata; dedup test proves an existing
  UNFCCC seed report is not duplicated by the new layer, and that an
  OECD work already present via its 10.1787 DOI is not re-added.

## Verification

- [ ] Inclusion rule and document list validated by the author
- [ ] Layer present in the regenerated corpus with correct provenance flags
- [ ] v1 subset reproducible via `in_v1` after the rerun

## Invariants

- Phase separation (manuscript build never triggers Phase 1); `in_v1`
  reproducibility; no hand-curated numbers in the paper.

